## What we are building

A thin, append-only event log for the level-5 class shell, with one minimal shared vocabulary and a single static author report as its first consumer. No inference, no runtime adaptation, no repo mutation during flow.

## Schema, locked

- **Event envelope, required on every event:**
  - `ts` (monotonic sequence + wall clock)
  - `actor` (one of: `student`, `tutor`, `worker_agent`, `background_job`, `script_supervisor`, `filesystem_artifact`)
  - `stage_id` (current stage event id)
  - `seq` (monotonic per session)
  - optional correlation IDs: `job_id`, `artifact_id`, `detour_id`, `suggestion_id`
- **Stage events:** append-only. No scalar `current_stage`. Each stage entry is its own event with `stage_id`, `name` from vocab, `entered_at`. Stage exit is a separate event referencing the same `stage_id`.
- **Tutor decision events, write-only at runtime:**
  - `enter_inspection`, `accept_detour`, `return_to_path`, `advance_stage`, `close_topic`, `record_suggestion`
  - Nothing in the runtime reads these. Reports and replay are the only consumers.
- **Suggestion events:**
  - `suggestion_candidate` at detection, written to a session-local file only.
  - `suggestion_confirmed` only at session-close, only after explicit confirmation.
  - No write to `course/suggestions/` until confirmation.
- **Detours:** every detour gets a fresh `detour_id`. `accept_detour` opens it; `return_to_path` closes it with the same id. Unclosed detours show up in the report.

## `course-vocab.yaml`, locked scope

Four fields, nothing else:

- `stages`
- `artifact_kinds`
- `tutor_intents`
- `suggestion_categories`

No student state. No concept mastery. No scoring language. Class files validate against this vocab. Plan-vs-actual is a string match over it.

## Vertical slice discipline

- One migration only. Everything above ships together or none of it ships.
- Every defined event must be emitted in the first human class. No optional ghosts.
- The author report is the acceptance test. If the report cannot render a section, the corresponding events are not done.
- Pre-commit check: class files may only reference vocab tokens.

## First author report, scope locked

Sections, in order:

- Declared path (from class file)
- Actual path (from stage events)
- Plan-vs-actual diff (vocab string match)
- Detour and resume pairs, with unclosed detours called out
- Background jobs and artifacts, by correlation id
- What the student inspected
- Tutor intent histogram (counts only, no quality claims)
- Suggestion candidates with confirmed-or-rejected status

No scoring. No mastery. No quality language anywhere in the report.

## Explicitly deferred

- Shadow critic of any kind, including offline.
- Stance inference, student state inference, concept mastery.
- Runtime tutor adaptation driven by telemetry.
- Repo-mutating suggestion writes during flow.
- Full replay mode.
- Cross-repo generator.
- Tone or effort selector.
- Transcript cleaner as a separate tool. The actor-split log makes it a view.

## Experiment order

1. Ship the migration.
2. One human class on the new schema.
3. Self-play pass to fuzz the schema and surface gaps.
4. Second human class.
5. Decide, with evidence in hand, whether to add any offline critic, stance work, or cross-repo generator. Cross-repo generator is gated on at least three clean human sessions plus a non-trivial intent histogram.

## Evidence the slice worked

- A maintainer who did not run the class can reconstruct the session from the report alone.
- Worker prompts no longer appear in the student timeline.
- Stage progress is accurate and reflects scan, triage, analyse, critique, review, and improvement capture.
- At least one detour and matching resume are visible.
- At least one `suggestion_candidate` is detected before any student prompt.
- The author edits the class file in response to the report within an hour of the session.
- Self-play surfaces at least one schema gap before the second human class runs.

## Abort or revise triggers

- After two human sessions, if the tutor intent histogram is monotonic or skipped, demote intent tags to post-session author annotation and stop emitting them at runtime.
- If plan-vs-actual requires fuzzy interpretation despite the vocab, simplify the class path model before adding any new telemetry.
- If any event in the schema is regularly missing or inconsistently emitted, remove it from the schema rather than patching consumers.

## Strongest argument for the position we did not take

The pure flight-recorder position would have shipped only actor split, stage timeline, and the report, with no tutor decision events at all. That would have been safer, smaller, and more clearly attributable. The risk we are accepting by including tutor intent tags is that the first migration is wider than strictly required, and that one of the six intents will turn out to be useless. We accept that risk because pure description across repeated sessions is likely to hide the variable that carried the experience, namely the tutor's choices. The abort trigger above is the safety valve.

